-- Marketing tables + security-relevant indexes. `contacts` is NOT created here:
-- it already exists via migrations/0002_crm.sql (id UUID, name, phone, email,
-- tags, stage, notes, next_followup, consent_sms, consent_email, source,
-- created). This migration only adds campaigns / sends / suppressions and the
-- indexes the consent/suppression guard needs to be correct AND fast.
--
-- Timestamp convention for THESE tables: `ts` and `scheduled_at` are INTEGER
-- epoch milliseconds (Date.now()). This is intentionally different from the
-- pre-existing contacts.created (ISO string); the two never mix within a table.
-- File is named 0001 to sit before 0002_crm.sql, but every statement is
-- idempotent (IF NOT EXISTS), so apply order does not matter.

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS campaigns (
  id           TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  channel      TEXT NOT NULL CHECK (channel IN ('sms','email')),
  name         TEXT NOT NULL,
  subject      TEXT DEFAULT '',            -- email only
  body         TEXT NOT NULL,              -- supports {{name}} merge
  tag_filter   TEXT DEFAULT '',            -- single tag; '' = whole list
  status       TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'draft'
                 CHECK (status IN ('draft','scheduled','sending','sent','paused')),
  scheduled_at INTEGER,                    -- epoch ms; NULL for send-now
  created      INTEGER NOT NULL            -- epoch ms
);

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS sends (
  id          TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
  campaign_id TEXT NOT NULL,
  contact_id  TEXT NOT NULL,
  channel     TEXT NOT NULL CHECK (channel IN ('sms','email')),
  status      TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'queued'
                CHECK (status IN ('queued','sent','delivered','failed','suppressed')),
  provider_id TEXT DEFAULT '',
  error       TEXT DEFAULT '',
  ts          INTEGER NOT NULL             -- epoch ms
);

-- Suppressions keyed by (channel, value) so suppress() UPSERT and the guard's
-- NOT EXISTS are O(index). `value` is the NORMALIZED phone (E.164, via crm.js
-- normPhone) or the lowercased email.
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS suppressions (
  channel TEXT NOT NULL CHECK (channel IN ('sms','email')),
  value   TEXT NOT NULL,
  reason  TEXT DEFAULT '',
  ts      INTEGER NOT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (channel, value)
);

-- One send per campaign+contact. Backs the guard's NOT EXISTS and de-dupes the
-- TOCTOU path; the write path should INSERT OR IGNORE against this.
CREATE UNIQUE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_sends_campaign_contact
  ON sends (campaign_id, contact_id);

-- Fast per-campaign stat rollups (queued/sent/failed/suppressed) for the UI.
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_sends_campaign_status ON sends (campaign_id, status);

-- Consent-filtered scans for recipient selection.
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_contacts_consent_sms   ON contacts (consent_sms);
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_contacts_consent_email ON contacts (consent_email);

-- Cron picks up due scheduled campaigns.
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_campaigns_status_sched ON campaigns (status, scheduled_at);

-- Suppression match happens on contact.phone / contact.email. crm.js already
-- creates idx_contacts_phone; add email to make the email-channel guard fast.
CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_contacts_email ON contacts (email);
=== END FILE ===

=== FILE: docs/admin/marketing-security-notes.md ===
# Marketing backend — security & compliance requirements (adversarial review)

These are the invariants the data-api, sms/twilio, email/resend, cron, and
admin-ui sections MUST satisfy. Each maps to a helper in
`src/marketing-security.js`. If a requirement is not visibly enforced by one of
those helpers at the point it matters, it is not enforced. The whole design
FAILS OPEN if the send pipeline re-implements recipient selection instead of
calling `sendableRecipientsSQL` + `stillSendable`.

## A. Authentication & authorization
- A1. EVERY `/api/admin/marketing/*` route is gated by `requireAdmin(req, env)`
  (constant-time). No marketing mutation is reachable without a valid session
  cookie or Bearer key. The router checks FIRST, before parsing bodies.
- A2. `isAdmin` fails closed if `ADMIN_KEY` is missing or < 16 chars.
- A3. Bearer key + session HMAC compared with `timingSafeEqual`, not `===`.
  (worker.js currently uses `===` at lines 34 and 44; see integration notes for
  the two-line upgrade that preserves existing sessions.)
- A4. Public marketing routes are exactly two: `POST /api/hooks/twilio` and
  `GET /u/:token`. Both are unauthenticated by necessity and MUST NOT expose any
  admin capability, contact enumeration, or DB write beyond suppress/opt-in for
  the specific verified value.

## B. Webhook (inbound SMS) integrity
- B1. `POST /api/hooks/twilio` verifies `X-Twilio-Signature` with
  `verifyTwilioSignature` (HMAC-SHA1 over `signedUrl + sorted params`, base64),
  constant-time. Missing/invalid signature => 403, no side effects.
- B2. The signed URL is built from `PUBLIC_URL` via `twilioSignedUrl`, not the
  request Host header. Set `PUBLIC_URL` to the exact origin Twilio calls
  (scheme + host, no trailing slash).
- B3. Inbound keywords use `classifyInboundKeyword` (first-token, word-boundary):
  STOP-family suppress + reply once, HELP replies with help text, START
  re-opts-in. The `From` number is normalized with `toSendablePhone` before any
  suppression match. Respond with `twimlMessage`/`twimlEmpty` (valid TwiML so
  Twilio does not log an error or retry).
- B4. Rate-limit the webhook per source number: `rateLimit(env, 'tw:'+from)`.

## C. Consent & suppression at SEND time (non-negotiable)
- C1. Recipient selection uses ONLY `sendableRecipientsSQL`: one parameterized
  query enforcing consent flag = 1, contact value present, NOT in suppressions,
  NOT already in `sends`, and the bound (wildcard-escaped) tag filter. No section
  builds its own recipient WHERE clause. One query per chunk, not two lookups per
  recipient — this respects the Workers subrequest budget.
- C2. Immediately before each provider call, re-check `stillSendable` (TOCTOU) so
  a STOP that landed mid-tick suppresses the queued message. A message failing
  this is written to `sends` with status `suppressed`, never sent.
- C3. STOP/unsubscribe are idempotent via `suppress` (UPSERT on (channel,value))
  and flip the matching contact's consent flag so the UI agrees with reality.
- C4. Suppression matching is on NORMALIZED values (E.164 via `normPhone`,
  lowercased email). Contacts and suppressions are normalized on write so a raw
  `(305) 555-1212` and a suppressed `+13055551212` match.

## D. Compliance content rules
- D1. Marketing SMS bodies pass through `shapeSmsBody` (appends "Txt STOP to opt
  out" if absent). Enforced in the send path, not the UI. Merge `{{name}}` AFTER
  shaping so a long name can't push the footer off.
- D2. Every marketing email includes a working unsubscribe link (`/u/<token>`
  from `makeUnsubToken`) AND a `List-Unsubscribe` header with both the https URL
  and a `mailto:`, plus `List-Unsubscribe-Post: List-Unsubscribe=One-Click`
  (RFC 8058, required by Google/Yahoo for bulk senders).
- D3. `runCron` calls `withinSmsQuietHours()` before dispatching SMS. Outside
  09:00–20:00 America/New_York the SMS chunk no-ops (campaign stays sending/
  scheduled); EMAIL is unaffected. Quiet-hours fails closed on any TZ error.
- D4. A campaign moves to `sending` only after a typed "SEND" confirm in the UI
  showing the live recipient count (see F/G). Scheduling stamps `scheduled_at`
  (epoch ms); the cron promotes `scheduled -> sending` when due.

## E. Injection & data integrity
- E1. 100% of D1 access uses `.bind(...)`. No string concatenation of user input
  into SQL. `sendableRecipientsSQL` binds the tag and escapes LIKE wildcards
  (`% _ \`); column names come from a fixed allowlist (`consent_sms|consent_email`,
  `phone|email`), never user input.
- E2. CSV import validates + stores raw values; any CSV EXPORT (and any value
  echoed into a downloadable file) runs through `stripCsvFormula` to defuse
  `= + - @` formula injection. Default consent flags to 0 on import.
- E3. `{{name}}` merge uses `renderTemplate`: CRLF/control stripped (blocks email
  header injection), length-capped, HTML-escaped for email bodies; unknown
  `{{tokens}}` removed, not reflected.
- E4. `normalizeEmail` rejects CR/LF/tab/NUL so a contact email can't inject
  extra headers into the Resend payload.

## F. Escaping (XSS in the admin panel)
- F1. Every value rendered into the admin DOM from contacts/campaigns/sends is
  wrapped in `esc()` (identical to the admin page's inline esc, line 134):
  names, phones, emails, tags, subjects, bodies, provider error strings, stats.
- F2. Provider error text stored in `sends.error` and shown in the UI is
  `esc()`'d — it is attacker-influenceable (e.g. an invalid address echoed back).

## G. Abuse & rate limits
- G1. Admin login is delayed on failure (existing 800 ms) AND rate-limited by
  `rateLimit(env, 'login:'+clientIp(req))`.
- G2. Test-send is restricted by `assertTestTarget` to `ADRIAN_PHONE` /
  `ADRIAN_EMAIL` ONLY (no fallback to TWILIO_FROM/EMAIL_FROM). The composer sends
  no destination for the test — otherwise the panel is an open relay. Also
  rate-limit test-send (e.g. 10/hr) to protect Twilio/Resend credit.
- G3. The cron processes a bounded chunk per tick (`sendableRecipientsSQL` LIMIT,
  default 50, hard-capped 500). One provider call per recipient; a thrown
  provider call marks that recipient `failed` and the tick continues.
- G4. `/u/:token` and the webhook are rate-limited so neither can hammer the DB.

## H. Email unsubscribe endpoint hardening
- H1. `GET /u/:token` verifies with `verifyUnsubToken`, then `suppress`es the
  embedded channel+value. It always returns 200 with the SAME friendly page for
  valid AND invalid/expired tokens, and never echoes the email or campaign name
  back — this prevents address enumeration via response differences.
- H2. `UNSUB_SECRET` is a SEPARATE secret from `ADMIN_KEY` (generate:
  `openssl rand -hex 32`). It falls back to ADMIN_KEY only if unset, so set it
  before launch so a leaked admin key can't forge opt-out links.

## I. Secrets & transport
- I1. Cookies keep `HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Strict` (already set). Admin JSON
  stays `Cache-Control: no-store`.
- I2. Secrets (`TWILIO_*`, `RESEND_API_KEY`, `EMAIL_FROM`, `ADMIN_KEY`,
  `UNSUB_SECRET`, `PUBLIC_URL`, `ADRIAN_PHONE`, `ADRIAN_EMAIL`) are Wrangler
  secrets, never in wrangler.toml or committed.
- I3. A2P 10DLC registration is an account-level Twilio prerequisite — carriers
  filter unregistered marketing traffic. Documented, not coded around.

## J. Legal minimums (operational, no code substitute)
- Every marketing email includes Adrian's physical mailing address; subjects not
  deceptive; opt-outs honored promptly (code does it immediately). SMS marketing
  requires prior express written consent; keep consent records (contacts.source
  + created serve this). CASL/TCPA/CAN-SPAM apply.
